fields.physical_description:
Obstetrics book "Nouvelles Démonstrations d'Accouchemens" by
 Jacques-Pierre Maygrier (1771-1835): folio book with an engraved
 portrait of the author on the frontispece, foreword, introduction,
 eighty pages of text, table of contents, and eighty engraved plates
 illustrating various aspects of the subject.  These include the
 development of the foetus, various techniques for delivery, the foetal
 skeleton (XXII), the obstetrician examining a standing patient (XXIX)
 and a prone one (XXX), obstetrical instruments (LXXIII-LXXVI),
 breast-feeding (LXXVII), and feeding vessels (LXXX).
fields.dimensions: Height: 42.2 cm folio, Width: 27.6 cm closed, Depth: 3.5 cm
fields.title: Nouvelles Démonstrations d'Accouchemens
fields.materials_techniques: Engraved and printed paper with half calf binding and marbled boards
fields.marks: BÉCHET, LIBRAIRE, PLACE DE L'ÉCOLE DE MÉDICINE, No.8 1822          (in pencil)  NO 118
fields.history_note:
References: 'The Womans Booke' by Ove Hagelin (Stockholm: Svenska
Läkaresällskapet, 1990): "...The rare first edition of
Maygrier's major work, the best and most magnificent
obstetrical atlas of the nineteenth century"
('Nouvelles Démonstrations d'Accouchemens' went through six editions and was translated into three other languages).

Written by Jacques-Pierre Maygrier (1771-1835), an army
surgeon who studied obstetrics with Antoine Dubois
(Empress Marie-Louise's accoucheur) in Paris, going on
to become an influential obstetrician in his own right,
with a number of published works to his credit.
fields.production_note:
Made by: Jacques-Pierre Maygrier (author); Antoine Chazal (illustr);Forestier & Couche (fils) (engravers); Béchet (publisher)
France
